value.0: A woman into her middle years, she looks very much like a matronly figure..

A middle aged man with a worn edge to his gaze. His accent has a clear South Cordor accent, voice rough and brassy. The company he keeps and lack of any emblem means he is most likely a caravan guard or mercenary.
Well crafted armor said to be made of Dragon hide for it's sheer protective nature.
This man with reddish hair has a smile on his face caught halfway between a playful grin and contemptuous sneer.
A man with a calm down to earth demeanour.
Designed to go on either sex, this suit with brown leather pants and grey shirt is stylish for lounging about the town.  It has a tag that reads: "Arwen E'lyn Designs."
This outfit is lovely, if alarming, with its dark colors, embroidered details, and severe lines.  However, when you're trying to make a statement, or a point, nothing else will do.
This colorful robe is marked all over with patterns that look vaguely like eyes.

Generations ago, the dwarven clan Dweomerpalm faced a plight: an expedition of mages from Thay were determined to gain control of the gem mines the dwarves controlled, and were bombarding the dwarven settlement with their destructive evocations. Having almost lost hope, the smiths of Keep Dweomer came up with an idea: They gathered every artisan and enchanter in the town to create suits of armor that would defy the elements themelves. Finally, enough such armors were finished to equip a retaliation army of the dwarves. Unfortunately for the Stout Folk, Thayvian diviners had revealed their plan and prepared something quite different. As the victoriously grinning dwarves charged, unshaken by the fireballs and bolts of lightning around them, devastating magic suddenly pierced and bent the poor dwarves’ minds. Those who didn’t fall into a coma fled into every possible direction, chased by both imaginary fiends and the summoned servants of the wizards. Without much opposition, the Thayvians slaughtered the remaining inhabitants of Keep Dweomer and took over the mines they yearned for.

With the unlucky dwarves who got lost and usually killed somewhere in the Upperdark or the Cold Lands, the infamous Thaybreakers, later named Armors of Universal Resistance by dry scholarly types, spread across Faerûn and can still be found in monsters’ hoards or the private collections of lucky aventurers. They come in various shapes, but all are adorned with various gems which contain the protective enchantments. Tymora must be fond of you, for you are holding one such armor of legends.
A young human girl with an easy smile and energetic bouncy disposiition. Her dress sense seems to favour things that compliment her red hair.
A quite young human lad, of fair skin and quiet demeanour.
A middle aged man, blessed with gold brown hair with no trace of gray or white. He wears the lavish robes of a Waukeenar and an ever present kind smile.
This serious looking, well-muscled woman with lightly graying hair wears a sigil of Waukeen upon her gilded armour. The goddess face captured in profile embossed upon the chestplate.

This metallic dragon towers over most normal sized buildings, it's well tended scales shine like burnished steel and the distinct scent of wet metal permeates the air around it.

The dragons face uniquely has many spines surrounding it's face, making it look more human-like and allowing a wider range of expression.

It's wings look almost like blades that overlap to form feathers, and the scales upon it's chest look almost like a shield.
OOC ring for all bosses, to protect against the more popular spells for instant death.
A dragon scale, coloured in a sapphire blue. It may be used repeatedly to ward against damage from electricity.
A halfling dressed in the robes of a Waukeenar
A dwarf with dark hair and kind eyes. Dressed in the fancy robes of the Waukeenar

A broadly build young human, dressed in blacksmith's attire and almost never seen without his trusty hammer and pliers.

He has steely gray eyes and a musk of wet steel that almost never leaves him.

Designed specifically for the person who says "Don't bother me now; I'm working."

Still, it does keep the heat off you a bit, when working with forges.
A hammer created in honor of the one used by Gond, Lord of All Smiths.

No doubt the brainchild of a twisted gnome, this hammer has the unique ability to spout clever one-liners as it strkes it's opponent.  Often doubling them over in laughter just as the head swings down from above....
A middle aged woman with a calm and wise demeanour.
A fiery dwarf with specks of gray in his beard.
A serious looking elf, impassive and detatched.

Stories speak of a poor traveller, victim to a snowstorm one winter night. In the midst of frostbite and unconsciousness, he stumbled upon an isolated monastery, dedicated to Ilmater. The monks took him in, gave him shelter, food and most notably, a pair of thick, snow-wading boots.

With new-found vigor, he left the next day, boots firmly clad. Winter gave way to spring, and spring gave way to further winters, until the man was wealthy enough to return to that secluded monastery, to give his thanks for supporting him at his time of need.

To his surprise, he could not find the monastery, no matter how hard he searched the land. The blizzard returned once more during his searches, covering the land in a white blanket. One quiet night resting in his makeshift shelter, he found a dying man, frozen half to death. After feeding him and nursing him to health, he gifted the man those same boots he received years prior, and decided to build a small monastery in place of the one he could no longer find.
Popular among strong wizards, these gloves affort them strength and mental dexterity to better practice their craft and control the weave.

This plain gold band is formed of sparkling gold, in simplicity and perfection.  It's unbroken perfect circle reflects eternity, the amount of time that the two people gathered to take part in this event are agreeing to love each other.  As this ring is placed upon one's finger, one feels a light twinge of magic, as if the very Gods themselves have born witness to your oaths, and watch in approval.
A minor ring of spell storage, typically used by Zhaunin wizards of The Sorcere.
This wide belt is made of thick leather and studded with iron. It grants the wearer the strength of a giant and the ability to make devastating melee attacks.

This smooth smoking pipe herb creates a relaxing euphoric feel to it's users; so much so that in some lands it is illegal...luckily, however, Cordor's authorities have long since recognized it's medicinal and beneficial side effects.

The Order of the Crouching Lemur are a monastic group who espouse endurance and strength of spirit in the face of adversity, and prove this by eking out an existence on a harsh mountain in the Skull Crags, beset on all sides by the environment and hostile creatures.

Despite their isolationist ways, they are surprisingly welcoming to outsiders, offering fine wares and supplies to those who can provide the coin. It isn't uncommon to find these robes in place as far as Brogendenstein, and this open nature has helped spread the word of the relatively small monastery across the land.

A small shield weaved with the fabric of the shadow plane itself, being both quieter than a normal shield and protecting outstandingly against spell which target the mind. Its heavy reliance on the shadows however, weakens the user against cold and negative energy...

This small shield is an odd creation of the Triumvir.  It is strange in that it is as much a songbook, as it is a shielding device.  Written all across the back of the shield are small runes that when the proper words are spoken, instantly become a projected song of the bard's choosing.  Setting specific songs and spells in the runes before hand in the shield makes it easier to sing them and cast them in battle.
